'''Footwork''' is a genre of music and [[street dance]] that originated in [[Chicago]] during the 1990s.<ref name=guardian>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/may/27/footwork-street-dance-chicago|title=Footwork takes competitive dancing to the Chicago streets|publisher=''[[The Guardian]]''|first=Hazel|last=Sheffield|date=2010-05-27|access-date=January 26, 2011}}</ref>

The dance involves fast movement of the feet with accompanying twists and turns, and usually takes place as part of a "[[Street dance#Battles|battle]]".<ref name=npr>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/therecord/2010/12/14/131834348/chicago-s-footwork-music-and-dance-get-a-transatlantic-lift|title=Chicago's Footwork Music And Dance Get A Transatlantic Lift|date=December 6, 2010|author=SAMI YENIGUN and WILLS GLASSPIEGEL|publisher=''[[National Public Radio]]''|access-date=January 26, 2011}}</ref> The style was popularized outside Chicago by inclusion in the [[music video]] for [[Dude 'n Nem]]'s 2007 single "Watch My Feet".<ref name=ChiReader>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagoreader.com/gyrobase/chicago-footwork-juke-house-dance-style-mtv/Content?oid=1604529&storyPage=2|title=Music for Feet:The Chicago dance style footwork already has MTV's attention. But footwork music may be too weird for mainstream ears.|first=Miles|last= Raymer|publisher=''[[Chicago Reader]]''|date=April 1, 2010|access-date=January 26, 2011}}</ref>

The music style has evolved from the earlier, rapid rhythms of [[Ghetto house#Chicago Juke|juke]] and ghetto house, a change pioneered by [[RP Boo|R.P. Boo]].<ref name=npr/> It may draw from styles such as [[drum and bass]], utilizing double-time clave triplets, syncopated toms and prominent [[sub-bass]].<ref name="guard">{{cite web|last1=Arnold|first1=Jacob|title=Fancy footwork: how Chicago's juke scene found its feet again|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/jun/30/fancy-footwork-how-chicagos-juke-scene-found-its-feet-again|website=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=3 May 2017}}</ref> Tracks also frequently feature heavily syncopated [[sample (music)|samples]] from [[rap music|rap]], [[pop music|pop]] and other sources, and are often around 160 bpm.<ref name="Spin">{{cite web|last1=Cush|first1=Andy|title=Jlin’s Rust Belt Modernism|url=http://www.spin.com/featured/jlin-may-2017-cover-story/|website=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|accessdate=12 May 2017}}</ref> 
Footwork also incorporates the club culture cultivated in disco, house and techno.

Radio station [[Afropop Worldwide]] remarked on the genre and its developments in 2011, saying that:
{{cquote|The most recent development in house's evolution, however, is a sound called 'footwork'. On Friday evenings at the Underground Tracks Factory, teenagers face off and improvise footwork dance battles. Their feet fly at insane speeds, something of a cross between house dance, tap dancing and breakdancing footwork. It looks like a dance from another dimension. The music they dance to is related to juke, but it's way more spacious, with more rhythmic complexity. Some tracks like "Reverb" by DJ Rashad are downright experimental walls of pulsating noise that would make [[John Cage]] proud. All these styles speak to the truth that house music never really left Chicago, as is often said. Its legacy continues to reverberate and mutate throughout the city.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Midwest Electric: The Story of Chicago House and Detroit Techno |episodelink= |url=http://www.afropop.org/radio/radio_program/ID/826 |access-date=June 17, 2011 |series=[[Afropop Worldwide]] |serieslink=|credits= |network=[[Public Radio International]] |airdate=2011-06-16 |time=7:30 }}</ref>}}

